<tr><td> </td><td class='diff-context'>Before you can play a map you have to compile it. The easiest way is to select BSP &gt; BSP in the map editor, but you can also type &quot;[[dmap (console command)|dmap]] &lt;mymap&gt;&quot; in the console. Doom 3 is different from previous id engines because it reads direct from .[[MAP (file format)|MAP]] files without making computations for VIS and LIGHT, which are performed on-the-fly by the engine. However, you still need to 'compile' your maps to create a .[[CM (file format)|CM]] and a .[[PROC (file format)|PROC]] which essentially makes solid geometry solid. Despite this, map compilation is very fast (measured in seconds).</td><td> </td><td class='diff-context'>Before you can play a map you have to compile it. The easiest way is to select BSP &gt; BSP in the map editor, but you can also type &quot;[[dmap (console command)|dmap]] &lt;mymap&gt;&quot; in the console. Doom 3 is different from previous id engines because it reads direct from .[[MAP (file format)|MAP]] files without making computations for VIS and LIGHT, which are performed on-the-fly by the engine. However, you still need to 'compile' your maps to create a .[[CM (file format)|CM]] and a .[[PROC (file format)|PROC]] which essentially makes solid geometry solid. Despite this, map compilation is very fast (measured in seconds).</td></tr>
